It is still useless for me if you have struct with &#x27;packed&#x27; attribute
ie: <a href="http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/fs/btrfs/ctree.h#L220" rel="nofollow">http://lxr.free-electrons.com/source/fs/btrfs/ctree.h#L220</a><p><pre><code>  // +build ignore
  package tmp
  /*
  #include <btrfs/ctree.h>
  */
  import &quot;C&quot;
  // 220 struct btrfs_disk_key {
  // 221         __le64 objectid;
  // 222         u8 type;
  // 223         __le64 offset;
  // 224 } __attribute__ ((__packed__));
  type BtrfsDiskKey C.struct_btrfs_disk_key
</code></pre>
Output:<p><pre><code>  $ go tool cgo -godefs test.go 
  // Created by cgo -godefs - DO NOT EDIT
  // cgo -godefs test.go
  package tmp
  type BtrfsDiskKey struct {
	Objectid	uint64
	Type		uint8
	Pad_cgo_0	[8]byte
  }
</code></pre>
After all the experiments I created my own helper[1], which helps map C structure(even packed) to Go structure using reflect package.<p>[1] <a href="https://github.com/plar/btrfs/blob/master/ioctl/mappings.go" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/plar/btrfs/blob/master/ioctl/mappings.go</a>
